    content: `<img src="https://source.unsplash.com/1200x800/?healthcare&sig=501&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80&fm=webp" alt="Vitamins and supplements" loading="lazy" style="max-width:100%; border-radius:8px;" />

<p>Supplements are everywhere with claims of health benefits. Understanding supplement evidence and needs helps you make informed choices rather than wasting money on unnecessary products.</p>

<h2>Vitamin and Mineral Basics</h2>
<p>Vitamins are organic compounds your body can't produce—you need dietary sources. Minerals like calcium and iron come from food. Most people meet needs through balanced diet. Vitamin deficiencies exist but are less common in developed countries. Supplementing when you don't have a deficiency doesn't provide additional benefits. Too much of some vitamins causes toxicity. Food provides vitamins plus beneficial compounds supplements lack. Focus on adequate diet first, supplementation second.</p>

<img src="https://source.unsplash.com/1200x800/?healthcare&sig=501&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80&fm=webp" alt="Dietary sources of nutrients" loading="lazy" style="max-width:100%; border-radius:8px;" />

<h2>Evidence for Common Supplements</h2>
<p>Vitamin D supplementation proves beneficial for many, especially those with limited sun exposure. B vitamins are essential; deficiency is uncommon. Vitamin C doesn't prevent colds despite popular belief. Multivitamins don't prevent disease in most people. Omega-3 supplements show modest benefits for heart health. Probiotics show promise for specific conditions but aren't universally beneficial. Herbal supplements have varying evidence—some help, many lack evidence. Research individual supplements you're considering rather than assuming efficacy.</p>

<h2>Safety Considerations</h2>
<p>Supplements interactions with medications are real. Fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, K) accumulate in your body—excess causes toxicity. Quality varies among brands. Third-party testing verifies content but isn't required. Adverse effects go unreported. Contamination with unlisted ingredients occurs. Supplements aren't regulated as strictly as drugs. FDA doesn't approve supplements before marketing. Pregnant women and children need additional safety consideration. Tell your healthcare provider about supplements you're taking.</p>

<img src="https://source.unsplash.com/1200x800/?healthcare&sig=501&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80&fm=webp" alt="Medical consultation about supplementation" loading="lazy" style="max-width:100%; border-radius:8px;" />

<h2>Making Smart Choices</h2>
<p>Have your nutrient levels tested—don't supplement guessing. Take supplements with purpose not routine. Choose third-party tested products. Check expiration dates. Know what you're taking and why. Review evidence and ask healthcare providers. Stop supplements that don't provide benefit to avoid unnecessary cost and risk. Food provides optimal nutrient forms and ratios. Whole foods offer benefits supplements can't replicate. Supplements supplement an adequate diet, not replace one.</p>

<img src="https://source.unsplash.com/1200x800/?healthcare&sig=501&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1200&q=80&fm=webp" alt="Nutrition planning and wellness" loading="lazy" style="max-width:100%; border-radius:8px;" />

<h2>FAQ</h2>
<p><strong>Should everyone take a multivitamin?</strong> No. Most people eating varied diets don't need multivitamins. Specific deficiencies warrant targeted supplementation.</p>
<p><strong>Are natural supplements safer than synthetic?</strong> No. "Natural" doesn't mean safe. Both natural and synthetic versions can cause harm in excess.</p>
<p><strong>How long can I take supplements?</strong> This depends on the supplement and your individual situation. Discuss ongoing use with your healthcare provider.</p>

<hr/>
<div style="background:#f5f7fa; padding:15px; border-radius:8px; margin-top:20px;">
  <p><strong>Author:</strong> SixHealth Editorial Team</p>
  <p><strong>Medical Review:</strong> SixHealth Clinical Team</p>
  <p><strong>Last Updated:</strong> 2026</p>
</div>`
